","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Roche","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aidan, Declan, Eamonn, Fergus, Fionnuala, Kevin Patrick, Liam.","Irish (Munster) and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Roach  . Compare   Roch  .","French: topographic name for someone who lived by a rocky outcrop or crag, from Old French <i>roche</i> ‘rock’. In North America, this surname is also a shortened form of the variant   Laroche   2. Compare   Deroche  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Laroche","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Fernand, Normand, Pierre, Jacques, Laurent, Adrien, Cecile, Germain, Marcel.","French:","habitational name from any of numerous places in various parts of France named Laroche or La Roche, from Old French <i>roche</i> ‘rock’, with feminine definite article <i>la</i>."]},{"name":"Larocque","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Fernand, Henri, Marcel, Normand, Valmore, Yves, Achille, Amie, Donat, Emile.","French: habitational name from La Ro(c)que, the name of several places in various parts of France, from a regional variant of <i>roche</i> ‘rock’ (see   Roche  , compare   Laroche  ), with feminine definite article <i>la</i>. Compare   Laroque  .","Altered form of southern French <b>Roquebrune</b> or of its variant <b>Rocquebrune</b>: habitational name from Ro(c)quebrune, the name of several places in the southern part of France. The surname <i>Roquebrune</i> is rare in France, while the variant <i>Rocquebrune</i> is extinct there. Compare   Larock  ,   Lerocque  ,   Rockburn  , and   Rocque   1."]},{"name":"Rochet","meanings":["French: diminutive of   Roche  , a topographic name meaning ‘rock’, or a habitational name from (Le) Rochet, the name of several places in various parts of France.","Catalan: of French origin (see above). This surname is also found in the Dominican Republic and Puerto Rico."]},{"name":"Rochat","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Monique, Philippe, Pierre.","French: topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>roche</i> ‘rock’ (see   Roche   2), or a habitational name from Le Rochat, the name of several places in the eastern part of France."]},{"name":"Roach","meanings":["English:","of Norman origin, from Old French and Middle English <i>roche</i> ‘rock, cliff, promontory’, sometimes a translation of   Stone  . The surname may have been topographic, denoting someone who lived on or by a prominent rock or rocky place, or a habitational name for someone who lived or came from a place so named, such as one of those called Roque or Roche(s) in Normandy and neighboring regions, or Roche in Cornwall, Roach Farm in Clyst Hydon (Devon), or Roch in Pembrokeshire (see   Roch  ).","in Lancashire perhaps referring to the River Roch, which runs through Rochdale; the river name is probably a back-formation from <i>Recedham</i>, an early name for Rochdale recorded in 1086, derived from Old English <i>reced</i> ‘building, house, hall’ + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’. Alternatively, the Lancashire name could be a shortened form of the now rare or extinct surname <b>Rochdale</b> alias <b>Rachedale</b>, <i>Rachdall</i>, a habitational name from Rochdale (Lancashire). From the 18th century onward the name is difficult to distinguish from   Roch  , borne by Irish migrants to South Lancashire, especially Liverpool."]},{"name":"Roquet","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Camille.","French: topographic name from a diminutive of <i>roche</i> ‘rock’ (see   Roche   and   Roque  ), or a habitational name from (Le) Roquet, the name of several places in various parts of France."]},{"name":"Rochez","meanings":["Walloon and French: variant of   Roche   2 or   Rocher  ."]}]},{"name":"Maurice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Late Latin name <i>Mauricius</i>, a derivative of <i>Maurus</i> (a byname meaning ‘Moor’, i.e. ‘dark, swarthy’), borne by, among others, an early Byzantine emperor (  <i>c.</i>539–602 ). It was introduced to Britain by the Normans and was popular in the Middle English period, but was not widely adopted by the nobility and became rare in the 17th century. Between the mid-19th century and the 1940s, it was moderately popular but has since faded again.  See also  Morris ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"FitzJohn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: relationship name from Anglo-Norman French  <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (  see  Fitz  ) + the personal name   John  , ‘son of  <i>John</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]},{"name":"Fidgeon","meanings":["1  English: (i) variant of   Vivian  .  Compare  Videan  . (ii) variant of   Fitzjohn  .","2  Irish: reduced variant of  <b>Mag Guagáin</b>,  see  McGuigan  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]},{"name":"la","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Orchid’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maurice FitzJohn de la Roche was born in 1375, in Fermoy, County Cork, Ireland, his father, John de La Roche, was 25 and his mother, Lady Amy MacCarthy, was 23. He married Amy FitzMaurice in 1396, in Fermoy, County Cork, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. In 1422, at the age of 47, his occupation is listed as sheriff of cork. He died in 1439, in his hometown, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1375–1439":"1375–1439","1377–Female":"1377–Surnud","1397–1435":"1397–1435","1400–1488":"1400–1488","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1352–1375":"1352–1375","1396":"1396","1374":"1374","1352":"1352","1350":"1350","1435":"1435","1422":"1422","1488":"1488","1400":"1400","1377":"1377","1387":"1387","1375":"1375","1397":"1397","about 1400":"umbes 1400","1439":"1439","Fermoy, County Cork, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Iirimaa","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Cork 1, Cork, County Cork, Ireland":"Cork 1, Cork, County Cork, Iirimaa","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1375–1439":"1375–1439","1377–Female":"1377–Kuollut","1397–1435":"1397–1435","1400–1488":"1400–1488","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1352–1375":"1352–1375","1396":"1396","1374":"1374","1352":"1352","1350":"1350","1435":"1435","1422":"1422","1488":"1488","1400":"1400","1377":"1377","1387":"1387","1375":"